<p class="page-intro">The Internet did not appear all at once, and it was never the invention of a single person, institution, or company. It emerged across decades of research, public funding, engineering work, academic cooperation, standards development, and cultural experimentation. What we now call the Internet is really the outcome of many overlapping histories: computer networking, packet switching, host addressing, open protocol design, distributed governance, and later the creation of the World Wide Web. To understand why the modern network looks the way it does, it helps to begin not with websites or apps, but with the research climate of the 1960s.</p>

<section class="history-section">
    <h2>Why this history matters</h2>
    <p>It is easy to think of the Internet only in terms of the present: search engines, social platforms, video streaming, online shopping, smartphones, and AI systems layered over global data centres. Yet the deeper history matters because many of the arguments we still have today were present from the start. Questions about openness, control, interoperability, standards, surveillance, commercialisation, and public infrastructure did not suddenly appear in the twenty-first century. They are woven into the network's DNA.</p>
    <p>The Internet also has a preservation problem. Important early documents survive only in archives, mirrors, private collections, or text dumps that can easily be lost. The same is true of BBS culture, mailing lists, early homepages, FAQs, and technical texts that shaped online life long before today's platforms. That is one reason this directory exists: not merely to point at surviving sites, but to provide context, continuity, and a curated path into a past that has become harder to discover.</p>
</section>

<section class="history-section">
    <h2>DARPA, time-sharing, and the research climate of the 1960s</h2>
    <p>The institutional starting point for Internet history is usually the <a href="https://www.darpa.mil/about-us/timeline/arpa-established" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Advanced Research Projects Agency</a>, established by the United States Department of Defense in 1958 after the shock of Sputnik. ARPA, later renamed DARPA, was designed to fund advanced scientific and technical work that might be strategically important. Computing soon became one of its most significant areas of interest. In the early 1960s, computers were rare, expensive, and usually isolated from one another. Universities and research laboratories might each have their own large machine, but direct communication between those machines was limited and awkward.</p>
    <p>At the same time, important conceptual changes were underway. Time-sharing systems were showing that computers did not have to be treated only as batch-processing machines. Researchers began to imagine a more interactive model in which many users could work with computing resources in real time. One of the most influential thinkers of the era, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._C._R._Licklider" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">J. C. R. Licklider</a>, wrote about an "Intergalactic Computer Network" in which people could access programs and data across multiple sites. It was still only a vision, but it was a remarkably clear anticipation of networked computing on a global scale.</p>
    <p>A second major breakthrough was packet switching. Traditional telephone systems established a dedicated circuit between two points for the duration of a conversation. For data communication, that model was inefficient and inflexible. Instead, packet switching broke information into smaller units, routed them across a network, and reassembled them at the destination. Work by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Baran" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Paul Baran</a> in the United States and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Davies" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Donald Davies</a> at the United Kingdom's National Physical Laboratory helped define this approach. Packet switching would become one of the foundations of the Internet.</p>
</section>

