<section class="history-section">
    <h2>ARPANET and the first networked communities</h2>
    <p>In 1969, ARPA funded the creation of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ARPANET" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ARPANET</a>, the first large-scale operational packet-switched network. Its early purpose was practical and experimental: connect institutions already funded by ARPA so they could share computing resources, software, and research output. But one of ARPANET's most important consequences was social rather than purely technical. Once people were connected, they began to communicate in ways that went far beyond resource sharing.</p>
    <p>Email, introduced by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Tomlinson" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Ray Tomlinson</a> in 1971, quickly became the dominant use of the network. Mailing lists followed, and with them came technical discussion, informal conversation, community norms, conflict, humour, etiquette, and collaborative problem-solving. In other words, the network almost immediately became a social medium. This is one of the recurring patterns of Internet history: systems built for technical use rapidly become places where people form communities.</p>
    <p>ARPANET also demonstrated an enduring principle of network design: openness to adaptation matters more than rigid original intent. What made the network important was not only what it was built to do, but what users discovered they could do with it once connection became possible.</p>
</section>

<section class="history-section">
    <h2>TCP/IP and the birth of the Internet</h2>
    <p>During the 1970s, separate networks were being built for different environments: military networks, university systems, radio-based links, and satellite communication projects. The problem was no longer simply how to build a network, but how to connect many different networks together. That challenge led to the work of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vint_Cerf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Vint Cerf</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Kahn" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Bob Kahn</a>, who developed the protocol suite that became <a href="https://www.rfc-editor.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">TCP/IP</a>.</p>
    <p>The significance of TCP/IP is hard to overstate. It allowed separate networks to interoperate without forcing them all to be identical. That is why the Internet is often described as a <em>network of networks</em>. Rather than being one centrally owned system, it became an architecture for interconnection. Networks could differ internally, yet still exchange traffic through shared protocols. This flexibility helped make growth possible.</p>
    <p>On <strong>1 January 1983</strong>, ARPANET officially transitioned to TCP/IP. Many historians regard this as the formal birth of the modern Internet. Around the same period, the development of the <a href="https://www.iana.org/domains/root/files" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Domain Name System</a> made the growing network more navigable by replacing hard-to-remember numerical addresses with names. This was a practical step, but also a cultural one. Naming systems made the network easier to inhabit.</p>
</section>

<section class="history-section history-highlight">
    <h2>Standards, RFCs, and the culture of open documentation</h2>
    <p>One of the least glamorous but most important parts of Internet history is the standards process. The Internet did not scale simply because of clever engineering. It scaled because people documented systems openly, circulated technical proposals, argued in public, revised drafts, and gradually converged on workable standards. The <a href="https://www.rfc-editor.org/retrieve/browse/rfc-index.txt" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Request for Comments</a> series is one of the great documentary records of the networked age.</p>
    <p>The RFC tradition mattered because it reflected an ethos: rough consensus, practical experimentation, and interoperability over proprietary lock-in. Figures such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Postel" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Jon Postel</a> played an enormous role in quietly stewarding this process. The Internet's development depended not just on invention, but on administration, editing, governance, and the social discipline of standardisation.</p>
</section>

