<section class="history-section">
    <h2>Academic expansion, Usenet, and BBS culture</h2>
    <p>In the 1980s, the network broadened beyond defence-related research. <a href="https://www.nsf.gov/od/lpa/nsf50/nsf883.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NSFNET</a>, funded by the United States National Science Foundation, played a major role in linking academic institutions and widening backbone access. The networked world was still specialised, but it was no longer confined to a narrow research environment.</p>
    <p>This was also the era in which many enduring forms of online culture took shape. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Usenet" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Usenet</a>, created in 1979, enabled distributed discussion through newsgroups. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bulletin_board_system" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Bulletin Board Systems</a> let users dial into local systems to exchange messages, files, software, and social chatter. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_Relay_Chat" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC</a>, introduced in 1988, created real-time networked conversation. Mailing lists flourished. FAQs emerged as a way of taming recurring questions. Moderation, fandom, technical help culture, pseudonymity, arguments, and community memory all developed well before the Web became dominant.</p>
    <p>That matters because the Internet already had a rich social life before websites became the public face of networking. The early web did not invent online culture. It provided a new publishing and navigation layer over cultures that were already lively, inventive, and sometimes unruly.</p>
</section>

<section class="history-section">
    <h2>The World Wide Web: a layer on top of the Internet</h2>
    <p>The Internet and the World Wide Web are not the same thing. The Internet is the underlying network infrastructure and protocol environment. The Web is an application layer built on top of it. That distinction matters historically because the Internet was already mature enough to support a new information system before the Web arrived.</p>
    <p>In 1989, <a href="https://home.cern/science/computing/birth-web" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Tim Berners-Lee at CERN</a> proposed a system for linking documents through hypertext over the Internet. His approach combined URLs for addressing, HTTP for resource transfer, and HTML for document structure. By 1991, the first website had gone live at <a href="https://info.cern.ch/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">info.cern.ch</a>. At that stage the Web was modest, technical, and largely confined to research communities. Yet the core architecture was there.</p>
    <p>The decisive expansion came with graphical browsers, especially <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mosaic_(web_browser)" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NCSA Mosaic</a> in 1993. Mosaic made the Web legible to non-specialists. Images could appear inline with text. Navigation became intuitive. The network felt less like a technical service and more like a medium. This was one of the turning points at which the Internet began to move from specialist infrastructure to mass public environment.</p>
</section>

