<section class="history-section">
    <h2>The early web: directories, portals, search, and homepages</h2>
    <p>As the Web grew in the mid-1990s, discovery became a problem. How were users supposed to find anything? Two broad approaches emerged. The first was the directory model. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yahoo!_Directory" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Yahoo Directory</a> began as a manually curated hierarchy of useful sites. <a href="https://curlie.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">DMOZ / the Open Directory Project</a> later expanded that principle at enormous scale through volunteer editors. Directories reflected a moment when the Web still seemed small enough to map by hand.</p>
    <p>The second approach was search. Systems such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AltaVista" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AltaVista</a>, Lycos, Excite, and others automated discovery by indexing pages and returning results by keyword. For a time, search engines, directories, and portal homepages existed side by side. A user might begin at Yahoo, switch to AltaVista, read news through a portal, then jump to a GeoCities page or a hobbyist site hosted on a personal domain.</p>
    <p>This was also the great age of the homepage. Services such as GeoCities, Tripod, and Angelfire gave ordinary people a place to publish. The result was a web that was messy, expressive, amateur, personal, and often gloriously inconsistent. Under construction GIFs, web rings, guestbooks, hit counters, tiled backgrounds, MIDI files, fan shrines, tutorials, rants, and niche expertise all flourished. Much of the emotional attachment people still feel to the "old web" comes from this period of visible individuality.</p>
</section>

<section class="history-section">
    <h2>The dot-com boom, bust, and consolidation</h2>
    <p>By the late 1990s, the Web had become not only a cultural phenomenon but a speculative financial one. Investors poured money into internet companies on the assumption that traffic and attention would eventually become profit. This was the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot-com_bubble" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">dot-com bubble</a>. Many companies grew rapidly without sustainable business models. In 2000 and 2001, much of that speculative structure collapsed.</p>
    <p>Yet the crash did not end the Internet. It filtered it. Some companies failed outright, while others survived, adapted, and became dominant. Amazon endured. E-commerce matured. Hosting improved. Broadband spread. The network moved from exuberant novelty towards durable everyday infrastructure. In a sense, the boom and bust accelerated the transition from experimental frontier to normalised environment.</p>
</section>

<section class="history-section">
    <h2>Google, Wikipedia, blogs, and Web 2.0</h2>
    <p>The early 2000s restructured the Web around search, participation, and user-generated content. <a href="https://about.google/our-story/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Google</a> came to dominate discovery through search, gradually replacing the old ecosystem in which directories, portals, and rival search engines all had meaningful market share. At the same time, <a href="https://www.wikipedia.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Wikipedia</a> demonstrated a new model of collaborative knowledge production: open, constantly revised, and global in scope.</p>
    <p>The blogosphere also mattered enormously. Blogging platforms lowered the barrier to publication and created a culture of linking, quoting, archiving, and public commentary that shaped online politics, journalism, and niche expertise for years. RSS readers, permalink structures, comments, and blogrolls formed an ecosystem that many people still regard as one of the richest periods in online writing.</p>
    <p>The phrase <em>Web 2.0</em> was never especially precise, but it captured a real shift. Users were no longer expected simply to consume content. They were expected to post, comment, upload, rate, remix, and maintain public identities through platforms. That shift led directly into the social media era.</p>
</section>

<section class="history-section">
    <h2>Platforms, smartphones, and the app-shaped Internet</h2>
    <p>In the 2010s, the Internet became increasingly concentrated around a small number of large platform companies. Search, social networking, online advertising, messaging, video hosting, app distribution, and cloud infrastructure all came to be dominated by a handful of firms. For many users, the Internet stopped feeling like a collection of places and started feeling like a small set of apps.</p>
    <p>Smartphones accelerated this transformation. The browser remained important, but much everyday activity migrated into enclosed app ecosystems. Discovery became more algorithmic. Feeds replaced browsing. Notifications replaced deliberate visits. The open web did not disappear, but it became less central to the average user's daily routine.</p>
    <p>This brought convenience, scale, and reliability, but it also brought concentration, surveillance, moderation disputes, platform dependence, and new forms of invisibility. Independent sites still existed, but they became harder to find without already knowing where to look. In that sense, the challenge facing the old web today is not only preservation. It is discoverability.</p>
</section>

<section class="history-section">
    <h2>The Internet now: infrastructure, memory, and preservation</h2>
    <p>The contemporary Internet supports cloud computing, streaming media, online education, software distribution, gaming, open-source collaboration, remote work, telemedicine, digital payments, and AI services. It is more deeply embedded in daily life than ever before. Yet at the same time, large parts of Internet history remain fragile. Links rot. Services shut down. Hosting bills go unpaid. Community forums vanish. Obscure file collections disappear. Older formats become difficult to access.</p>
    <p>This is why preservation matters. Projects such as the <a href="https://archive.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Internet Archive</a>, the <a href="https://web.archive.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Wayback Machine</a>, <a href="https://textfiles.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">textfiles.com</a>, standards repositories, academic collections, mirrors, and private archiving efforts all perform a vital historical function. The networked world has always generated more material than institutions can easily preserve. Much of what survives does so because individuals care enough to keep it alive.</p>
    <p>That spirit of preservation is also a continuation of early Internet culture. Long before everything became platform-centric, the network was built by people who documented, mirrored, explained, archived, and shared. The best parts of that ethos are still worth carrying forward.</p>
</section>

