<section class="history-section history-conclusion">
    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>The history of the Internet is not a neat march from one invention to the next. It is the story of overlapping systems: military research, academic networks, open standards, hobbyist communities, volunteer editors, commercial services, private platforms, and persistent archival efforts. It begins with packet switching and research funding, but it also includes BBS messages, Usenet threads, homepages, FAQs, browser wars, directory editors, search results, weblogs, forums, and the countless small acts of digital publishing that made the network human.</p>
    <p>Seen this way, the Internet is both infrastructure and culture. Understanding that longer history makes it easier to see the present more clearly. The network has changed before and it will change again. What matters is not only where it came from, but what survives, what remains discoverable, and what kinds of networked life people choose to preserve and build next.</p>
</section>
